This has a dependency on specific sensor name defined in a configuration file. Is it possible to look up the correct path to use?
Discussed offline. I will look into grabbing the Dbus objects and parsing them to find the correct one.
Used regex to match any current/future baseboard Dbus object and read the PwmName property if it exists.
Why this pattern? This will not work for system not use this naming convention
Is there a particular reason to prefer strcmp over an equality check? This is the format used in a similar function (findFruDevice) and thus I used it for consistency.
Addressed in latest patch. Will address the remaining comments in another patch.
Remove old system/new system, just say there are systems use customized pwm name with PwmName field in configuration file.
please be more specific show that how the system with a customized pwm name works.
Done - I wasn't sure if it was worth continuing if the interface is found but does not appear to contain the Index property, but I suppose it doesn't hurt to try to continue anyways.
this does not seem right - when line 315 fails
Uncertain I understand. If line 315 fails, then it will continue (now that I have implemented your requested change). So if line 315 fails, it should never hit return statement.
instance since Index is also 0 based
Is there a Set command need the same fix?
Thank you for that catch, I hadn't even thought of that for some reason.
This should continue to look for "Pwm" to handle fan and pwm don't use the same channel/index
The issue is not addressed correctly. The  change  does not fallback to find("Pwm"), which would be the Pwm channel for the fan instance. They are not always the same.

I see. I misunderstood your original intent. I will add this change. It is not how the command originally behaved, but it does sound like a better solution. However, should it prefer to check for Pwm over index then?
Yes, should look for "Pwm" which is the number for Pwm, Index if for fan tach.
More specific example: 6 should return Pwm_13 reading

Addressed these. Also, undid the change where you suggested changing "/" to "/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory". In testing, this broke the search. I could look into it further if you would like, but as it stands, it doesn't look like specifying /xyz/openbmc_project/inventory would save many loops and it works this way.

Please update if the following review lands

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/intel-ipmi-oem/+/57290

Modified commit message description and testing section to make note of this how instance is now treated as fan number rather than PWM number. As shown in the tested section, this change works on a system where a fan is plugged into a PWM pin of a different number.
Unintentionally left several log messages in this patch. Removing now.

ec{};

This is sufficient to initialize.
Also, the path is changing for this, so replace "/" with "/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory"

Done - Already aware of the ObjectManager changing, but this has not been merged yet and will break the object search if I implement this change before it has merged. I will make the change as soon as it is merged upstream.
Done - Also changed the one in the set command.
Addressed requests in review. Thank you Jonathan for modified commit message.
since you are using getManagedObjects, these two lines are unused
I moved these down to findFruDevice() which is still using them. I can make a separate commit to remove this from this function if it is something that is desired.
I am not sure that this should be const.
Done - Thanks for the reminder, I noticed the treewide change was merged upstream and implemented this.
